  </p>

  <!-- Case 1: Smart Compost -->
  <article class="card mt-8 p-6 sm:p-8">
    <header class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline justify-between gap-2">
      <h3 class="font-mono text-lg font-bold" style="color: var(--color-org-smart)">
        Smart Compost: an IoT platform sized for a tiny team
      </h3>
      <p class="font-mono text-xs text-faint">firmware to mobile, 2 engineers</p>
    </header>

    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-x-8 gap-y-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted sm:grid-cols-2">
      <p>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">need</span><br />
        Field hardware measuring compost piles for multiple customers. The sensor lineup would
        keep changing as the product learned, and at the start there was exactly one engineer:
        me.
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">decisions</span><br />
        Device traffic and human traffic enter through separate gateways: different auth,
        different failure tolerance. Behind them, domain services small enough for one person to
        own end to end. Telemetry is metric-first: a sensor catalog describes each metric, and
        readings reference the catalog instead of hardcoding one column per sensor. New hardware
        lands as catalog rows, not schema migrations. Risky launches hide behind feature flags
        per environment.
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">trade-offs</span><br />
        The metric-first model taxes ad-hoc SQL, paid deliberately because hardware iteration
        was the real constraint. Many small services add deploy surface, paid back by
        independent shipping once the team became two.
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">outcome</span><br />
        The platform runs from C++ firmware through the cloud to a React Native app, operated by
        two engineers, and the same catalog powers a public API and an MCP server for LLMs.
      </p>
    </div>

